Robotic Process Automation is technology that gives users the ability to program software or create robots to emulate user RPA Robots can integrate with multiple existing applications to complete business They can interact with the user interface to capture information and navigate and interact with systems in the same manner that a human user They can be designed to interpret information, send responses and communicate with other systems to undertake repetitive, or tasks, some of which were not previously achievable with The benefits of using robots are numerous they don’t sleep, make no errors, and require fewer overheads or Managed via a central Control Centre you can have complete visibility of all the work your new “digital workforce” is doing, and orchestrate their ​ At Tquila we adopt an automation first mindset to enable your company to adapt rapidly to an ever changing technological By automating more we unburden your employees from the boring, repetitive, tasks and allow them to focus on more qualitative, customer centred We believe that automating sooner rather than later can also identify problem areas within processes, applications and ​ ​ Hyperautomation , a term recently coined by Gartner, refers to the combination of a number of new technologies, and a clear strategy as to how they can help your business enter a new age of This approach is core to our business, and allows us to provide the right solutions in the correct manner to our ​ Starting with RPA as a core module integrating each of these technologies such as Process Discovery, OCR and Intelligent Data Capture, BPM, Chatbots, Machine Learning, Cognitive Services and Analytics . The combination of these creates automation and unleashes previously unreachable potential for your ​ To read more about hyperautomation and why it is important for you, check out our blog for articles and contact us to ensure you are ready for Trusted the world over Teams of every size, shape and kind have already made TQA the place where their work “As an official partner of ours, we trust the capabilities of the Tquila Automation team to support customers on their Hyperautomation They have proven their knowledge and expertise can be relied upon, and we re excited to see them expand rapidly in the intelligent automation space” — Chris Duddridge, Managing Director, UiPath Technology Partners Learn more in depth how we can help your company grow WHAT WE DO Social Linkedin Medium ​ Pages Home Who we are What we do Insights Contact Email Address Copyright Tquila Automation Privacy Policy Terms of Service

About News TEAM JOBS Contact us Sign in Change the way you see your city move — Meet Replica is a urban planning tool that can help cities answer key transportation Watch our video to learn more… Better data, better decisions Replica offers public agencies, land developers, and the community at large a complete sense of city movement The result is a higher confidence in critical transportation and land use FRESHER DATA We create a new Replica every three months allowing comparisons of trip patterns over time and showing how people respond to new infrastructure and policies on the A MORE DETAILED PICTURE We replicate trip data for every street and transit route, every neighborhood and census tract, every moment of the GREATER PRECISION We calibrate our models against data from public agencies to ensure accuracy and Built to protect privacy Replica maintains fidelity without compromising We use a process to generate movement data that is equivalent to activities but not traceable to actual people or specific MOBILE LOCATION DATA We use mobile phone location data to generate travel behavior models — basically, a set of rules that represent how a person makes choices on where, when, why, and how to SYNTHETIC POPULATION GENERATION Separately, we use aggregate demographic information to create what planners call a “synthetic population”. This is a virtual population that is statistically representative of the real COMPUTER SIMULATION We then give each person in the virtual population a travel behavior model and use computer simulation to generate a week of activities–helping us confidently replicate trip patterns across a city or metro Answers in minutes, not months Cities are complex, but the tools we use to understand them don t have to Replica makes three things easier than ever before: Exploring data Filter data by time, mode, location, and Visualizing insights Create charts and maps to visualize your Exporting and sharing findings Download images, maps, and data tables to share with colleagues or the Applications all over the city Traditionally travel models have been limited in both scope and Replica can be used for both transportation planning and across many other City Operations When should we schedule water main repairs? best seat in the house, allows Space Explorers to experience the majesty of gliding through space while sipping a beverage of Nine reclining, plush seats, for eight Space Explorers and a panoramic Refreshments bar and cabinet for Lavatory below the main connection, with communications devices to enable live windows for excellent photography from inside the Sensors showing altitude, wind, and temperature throughout the Instrument trunk on the capsule’s roof and below deck for research Splashdown Cone at base allows for smooth landing on the Book Your Spaceflight THE SPACEBALLOON Our advanced spaceballoon is designed to operate in space where Spaceship Neptune The size of a football stadium, the spaceballon gently flies the capsule for ascent and It is proven technology that NASA and government agencies around the world have used for decades for flying large research telescopes and other scientific As far back as the , the first person to see the curvature of earth did so from beneath a spaceballoon like Spaceship Neptune’s. Connecting to the Database | Docs Â Docs Community Slack Home Getting Started Introduction CLI Backend Frontend Data Schema Tutorials Examples Edit this page Connecting to the Database currently provides connectors to the following databases: Database DB Type PostgreSQL postgres MySQL mysql AWS Athena athena AWS Redshift redshift MongoDB (via MongoDB Connector for BI) mongobi Google BigQuery bigquery MS SQL mssql ClickHouse clickhouse Snowflake snowflake Presto prestodb Hive SparkSQL (thrift) hive Oracle oracle If you d like to connect to a database which is not yet supported, you can create a driver Here s a simple guide . Configuring Connection for CLI Created Apps When you create a new service with the CLI , the will be generated to manage all connection The set of variables could be different based on your database For example, for PostgreSQL the will look like this: CUBEJS_DB_HOST=<YOUR_DB_HOST_HERE CUBEJS_DB_NAME=<YOUR_DB_NAME_HERE CUBEJS_DB_USER=<YOUR_DB_USER_HERE CUBEJS_DB_PASS=<YOUR_DB_PASS_HERE CUBEJS_DB_TYPE=postgres CUBEJS_API_SECRET=secret The table below shows which environment variables are used for different databases: Database Credentials PostgreSQL, MySQL, AWS Redshift, MS SQL, ClickHouse, Hive SparkSQL, Oracle CUBEJS_DB_HOST , CUBEJS_DB_PORT , CUBEJS_DB_NAME , CUBEJS_DB_USER , CUBEJS_DB_PASS AWS Athena CUBEJS_AWS_KEY , CUBEJS_AWS_SECRET , CUBEJS_AWS_REGION , CUBEJS_AWS_S3_OUTPUT_LOCATION Google Bigquery CUBEJS_DB_BQ_PROJECT_ID , CUBEJS_DB_BQ_KEY_FILE or CUBEJS_DB_BQ_CREDENTIALS MongoDB CUBEJS_DB_HOST , CUBEJS_DB_NAME , CUBEJS_DB_PORT , CUBEJS_DB_USER , CUBEJS_DB_PASS , CUBEJS_DB_SSL , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_CA , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_CERT , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_CIPHERS , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_PASSPHRASE Snowflake CUBEJS_DB_SNOWFLAKE_ACCOUNT , CUBEJS_DB_SNOWFLAKE_REGION , CUBEJS_DB_SNOWFLAKE_WAREHOUSE , CUBEJS_DB_SNOWFLAKE_ROLE , CUBEJS_DB_NAME , CUBEJS_DB_USER , CUBEJS_DB_PASS Presto CUBEJS_DB_HOST , CUBEJS_DB_PORT , CUBEJS_DB_CATALOG , CUBEJS_DB_SCHEMA , CUBEJS_DB_USER , CUBEJS_DB_PASS Notes MongoDB To use with MongoDB you need to install MongoDB Connector for You can download it here . Learn more about setup for MongoDB MongoDB Atlas Use CUBEJS_DB_SSL=true to enable SSL as MongoDB Atlas requires CUBEJS_DB_SSL_CA , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_CERT , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_CIPHERS , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_PASSPHRASE can be left AWS Athena For Athena, you ll need to specify the AWS access and secret keys with the access necessary to run Athena queries , and the target AWS region and S3 output location where query results are Google BigQuery In order to connect BigQuery to , you need to provide service account requires the service account to have BigQuery Data Viewer and BigQuery Job User roles You can set CUBEJS_DB_BQ_KEY_FILE environment variable with a path to JSON key Another way is to encode the key file with base64 : $ cat path to key-file.json | base64 Now you can set the CUBEJS_DB_BQ_CREDENTIALS environment variable with the Connecting to Multiple Databases supports connection to multiple databases Please refer to Multitenancy Guide to learn SSL supports connection via SSL for Postgres and Mongo . To enable it set CUBEJS_DB_SSL environment variable to true . Technology • Sherlock Biosciences Home About Us Team Technology News Careers Better diagnostic testing should be Overview Powerful platforms for disease Too often, today’s conventional testing methods are either limited or too At Sherlock, we are taking breakthrough technologies and making them easy to use in health care, in industrial settings, and in the Sherlock’s Engineering Biology platforms, SHERLOCK™ and INSPECTR™, offer the power of information when it’s needed, in virtually any By providing solutions, Sherlock possesses the tools and vision to address existing and emerging testing markets – a molecular diagnostic answer for any sample, any target, What if tools could be used not just to treat disease, but to detect it, too? Engineering Biology The term “Engineering Biology” refers to the techniques used to design, build and direct biological systems into tools that can improve human Sherlock is focused on using CRISPR and Synthetic Biology to develop an entirely new generation of diagnostics, beginning with the SHERLOCK and INSPECTR What is SHERLOCK™? SHERLOCK is an evolution of CRISPR technology, which others use to make precise edits in genetic SHERLOCK can detect the unique genetic fingerprints of virtually any DNA or RNA sequence in any organism or Developed by our founders and licensed exclusively from the Broad Institute, SHERLOCK is a method for single molecule detection of nucleic acid targets and stands for S pecific H igh Sensitivity E nzymatic R eporter un LOCK ing . It works by amplifying genetic sequences and programming a CRISPR molecule to detect the presence of a specific genetic signature in a sample, which can also be When it finds those signatures, the CRISPR enzyme is activated and releases a robust This signal can be adapted to work on a simple paper strip test, in laboratory equipment, or to provide an electrochemical readout that can be read with a mobile What is INSPECTR™? INSPECTR leverages the power of synthetic biology by using synthetic gene networks as programmable molecular diagnostic The INSPECTR platform enables the creation of , diagnostic tests that can be applied across multiple diseases and used in a variety of INSPECTR stands for In ternal S P airing E xpression C assette T ranslation R A synthetic molecular diagnostics platform, INSPECTR was developed by our founders and is licensed exclusively from the Wyss Institute of Harvard INSPECTR can be programmed to distinguish targets based on a single nucleotide without an instrument and at room When INSPECTR’s synthetic biosensors detect the presence of a nucleic acid target, a reporter protein is This protein output can be designed to generate a signal tailored to any medium, providing a simple diagnostic This novel approach enables the rapid development of molecular diagnostic tests that are low cost, and broadly Performance and Attributes Sherlock’s unique Engineering Biology platform advantages span virtually every important category of performance: Performance Highly sensitive (can detect a single molecule in a sample) Highly specific (accurately detects the target) Integrates well with other tests and lab setups Quantitative (measures amount of target present) Rapid design and delivery to partners In addition, Sherlock’s technologies have advantages that can create value for existing and new Sherlock’s platforms also deliver the following important attributes: Attributes Portable (can be used in many different settings) Native specimen testing (direct analysis of unprocessed samples) Rapid (results in under one hour) Low cost Sherlock’s diagnostics have the potential to make gold standard testing easier in a range of settings, whether in the field during a disease outbreak, in a laboratory, or even in users’ We are working hard so that SHERLOCK and INSPECTR can be used everywhere testing is Meet our team If you would like to discuss how our platform can be put to use in new ways, send us an email at . About News TEAM JOBS Contact us Sign in Change the way you see your city move — Meet Replica is a urban planning tool that can help cities answer key transportation Watch our video to learn more… Better data, better decisions Replica offers public agencies, land developers, and the community at large a complete sense of city movement The result is a higher confidence in critical transportation and land use FRESHER DATA We create a new Replica every three months allowing comparisons of trip patterns over time and showing how people respond to new infrastructure and policies on the A MORE DETAILED PICTURE We replicate trip data for every street and transit route, every neighborhood and census tract, every moment of the GREATER PRECISION We calibrate our models against data from public agencies to ensure accuracy and Built to protect privacy Replica maintains fidelity without compromising We use a process to generate movement data that is equivalent to activities but not traceable to actual people or specific MOBILE LOCATION DATA We use mobile phone location data to generate travel behavior models — basically, a set of rules that represent how a person makes choices on where, when, why, and how to SYNTHETIC POPULATION GENERATION Separately, we use aggregate demographic information to create what planners call a “synthetic population”. This is a virtual population that is statistically representative of the real COMPUTER SIMULATION We then give each person in the virtual population a travel behavior model and use computer simulation to generate a week of activities–helping us confidently replicate trip patterns across a city or metro Answers in minutes, not months Cities are complex, but the tools we use to understand them don t have to Replica makes three things easier than ever before: Exploring data Filter data by time, mode, location, and Visualizing insights Create charts and maps to visualize your Exporting and sharing findings Download images, maps, and data tables to share with colleagues or the Applications all over the city Traditionally travel models have been limited in both scope and Replica can be used for both transportation planning and across many other City Operations When should we schedule water main repairs? Connecting to the Database | Docs Â Docs Community Slack Home Getting Started Introduction CLI Backend Frontend Data Schema Tutorials Examples Edit this page Connecting to the Database currently provides connectors to the following databases: Database DB Type PostgreSQL postgres MySQL mysql AWS Athena athena AWS Redshift redshift MongoDB (via MongoDB Connector for BI) mongobi Google BigQuery bigquery MS SQL mssql ClickHouse clickhouse Snowflake snowflake Presto prestodb Hive SparkSQL (thrift) hive Oracle oracle If you d like to connect to a database which is not yet supported, you can create a driver Here s a simple guide . Configuring Connection for CLI Created Apps When you create a new service with the CLI , the will be generated to manage all connection The set of variables could be different based on your database For example, for PostgreSQL the will look like this: CUBEJS_DB_HOST=<YOUR_DB_HOST_HERE CUBEJS_DB_NAME=<YOUR_DB_NAME_HERE CUBEJS_DB_USER=<YOUR_DB_USER_HERE CUBEJS_DB_PASS=<YOUR_DB_PASS_HERE CUBEJS_DB_TYPE=postgres CUBEJS_API_SECRET=secret The table below shows which environment variables are used for different databases: Database Credentials PostgreSQL, MySQL, AWS Redshift, MS SQL, ClickHouse, Hive SparkSQL, Oracle CUBEJS_DB_HOST , CUBEJS_DB_PORT , CUBEJS_DB_NAME , CUBEJS_DB_USER , CUBEJS_DB_PASS AWS Athena CUBEJS_AWS_KEY , CUBEJS_AWS_SECRET , CUBEJS_AWS_REGION , CUBEJS_AWS_S3_OUTPUT_LOCATION Google Bigquery CUBEJS_DB_BQ_PROJECT_ID , CUBEJS_DB_BQ_KEY_FILE or CUBEJS_DB_BQ_CREDENTIALS MongoDB CUBEJS_DB_HOST , CUBEJS_DB_NAME , CUBEJS_DB_PORT , CUBEJS_DB_USER , CUBEJS_DB_PASS , CUBEJS_DB_SSL , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_CA , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_CERT , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_CIPHERS , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_PASSPHRASE Snowflake CUBEJS_DB_SNOWFLAKE_ACCOUNT , CUBEJS_DB_SNOWFLAKE_REGION , CUBEJS_DB_SNOWFLAKE_WAREHOUSE , CUBEJS_DB_SNOWFLAKE_ROLE , CUBEJS_DB_NAME , CUBEJS_DB_USER , CUBEJS_DB_PASS Presto CUBEJS_DB_HOST , CUBEJS_DB_PORT , CUBEJS_DB_CATALOG , CUBEJS_DB_SCHEMA , CUBEJS_DB_USER , CUBEJS_DB_PASS Notes MongoDB To use with MongoDB you need to install MongoDB Connector for You can download it here . Learn more about setup for MongoDB MongoDB Atlas Use CUBEJS_DB_SSL=true to enable SSL as MongoDB Atlas requires CUBEJS_DB_SSL_CA , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_CERT , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_CIPHERS , CUBEJS_DB_SSL_PASSPHRASE can be left AWS Athena For Athena, you ll need to specify the AWS access and secret keys with the access necessary to run Athena queries , and the target AWS region and S3 output location where query results are Google BigQuery In order to connect BigQuery to , you need to provide service account requires the service account to have BigQuery Data Viewer and BigQuery Job User roles You can set CUBEJS_DB_BQ_KEY_FILE environment variable with a path to JSON key Another way is to encode the key file with base64 : $ cat path to key-file.json | base64 Now you can set the CUBEJS_DB_BQ_CREDENTIALS environment variable with the Connecting to Multiple Databases supports connection to multiple databases Please refer to Multitenancy Guide to learn SSL supports connection via SSL for Postgres and Mongo . To enable it set CUBEJS_DB_SSL environment variable to true . Entering private practice amidst a global pandemic: One therapist’s journey — Heard Heard Entering private practice amidst a global pandemic: One therapist’s journey Andrew Riesen September 1, Written by Rachel Willimott, LCSW Share This Post Share on facebook Share on linkedin Share on twitter Share on email As I consulted the internet and fellow therapists, I came across a plethora of advice on how to transition into private Start and build a Join an insurance Find a Facebook group or referral I took the road less While my route into private practice is not a approach, I found that it taught me essential lessons in flexibility, faith in the process, and how authentic connections will always serve me As my internship in a college counseling center came to a close in , I saw the opportunity to transition into a different kind of therapy I longed for the autonomy and flexibility to focus on my passions outside of therapy (including writing!), while preserving a sense of community and Life was telling me to take a Do something Born and raised in Nevada, I started to explore clinical opportunities across the United At one point, I interviewed for positions in a variety of cities, including Boston, New York, Seattle, San Diego, and I now realize that during this time period, I was operating out of a sense of I come from working class I am the first in my family to obtain a college degree and a graduate I am the primary earner in my relationship and manage my family’s I do not have a financial safety net or deep Because of this, I felt pressure to not only market myself a certain way, but also to submit to work that felt secure, though less Fast forward to June I decided to join a small group practice in Oakland, My partner and I packed up our apartment and pets to start a new life in the Bay My fear and anxiety felt crippling that I waited for my caseload to fill while my partner struggled to find A personal loan offered a temporary reprieve, but every day I wondered if the pieces would fall into place before my loan This sense of powerlessness affected my clinical I was more available to clients, very willing to accommodate last minute rescheduling, and eager to accept any type of work that came my I also experienced power dynamics that made me feel small and When I felt uncomfortable with the leadership at the practice, I said While I valued work with my clients, I also knew I was not being my authentic As a trained behaviorist, I am well aware that ignoring problems rarely My discomfort and unhappiness within and around the workplace were inevitably felt by my After a few painful and honest conversations, I decided that the group practice was not a fit for Again, I toiled with the idea of starting my own practice, aiming to fulfill my desire for autonomy and However, what if I failed as a business owner? I felt terrified that my courageous move to the Bay Area would end in I was not ready to be a solo As a result, I joined another group practice spearheaded by a clinician who I had consulted with for several I felt incredibly fortunate to join this group Additionally, the clinic director encouraged me to build up my own practice on the Nevertheless, I still felt a sense of I had endured so much uncertainty and change only to wind up at another While sitting with my disappointment and grief in December , I created a transition plan to officially start my own I imposed a deadline of March I slowly chipped away at logistical tasks, including setting up a website (which I found creatively fulfilling), obtaining a business license as a sole proprietor, setting up practice documents such as informed consent, and creating care plans with my current I already had a work phone number and email as well as practice It was both invigorating to have freedom to make these decisions and intimidating to assume the role of a solo business I soaked up as much knowledge as I could to inform the practice decisions that I I also applied to companies that could supplement my practice with referrals as well as those that provided employee assistance I finally felt ready to launch my new clinical Then a global pandemic The first case of community transmission of was in California and suddenly my business worries felt both too big and too How could I start my own practice during a pandemic and survive? Would the success of my practice even matter if everything in the country fell apart? My partner was laid off and I sat on my couch, wondering where I would go if I broke my expensive lease in Oakland during a plummeting economic crisis and the spread of a virus that did not care about I am deeply grateful that I did not need to break that Many Bay Area companies started offering therapy to their employees, which allowed more people to seek help than I had open conversations with my clients about their ability to pay, allowing them to stay in therapy at sustainable Former clients contacted me to resume therapy to manage the stress of

Is there a way to optimize your cloud spend and dramatically lower it? What is Bitcoin? - Swan Bitcoin Home Blog FAQ Sign Up Log in What is Bitcoin? Posted 2 25 20 by Yan Pritzker Bitcoin is a peer to peer electronic cash , a new form of digital money that can be trans­ferred between people or computers without any trusted inter­me­diary (such as a bank) and whose issuance is not under the control of any single Think of a paper dollar or metal When you give that money to another person, they don’t need to know who you They just need to trust that the cash they get from you is not a Typically people do this with physical money using only their eyes and fingers or using special­ized testing equip­ment for more signif­i­cant The majority of payments in our digital society are made over the Internet using a middleman service: a credit card company like Visa, a digital payment provider such as PayPal or Apple Pay, or an online platform like WeChat in The movement toward digital payments brings with it the reliance on a central actor that has to approve and verify every The nature of money has changed from a physical object you can carry, transfer, and authen­ti­cate yourself to digital bits that have to be stored and verified by a third party that controls their As we give up our cash for conve­nient digital payments, we also create a system where we give extra­or­di­nary powers to those who would seek to oppress Digital payment platforms have become the basis of dystopian author­i­tarian methods of control, such as those used by the Chinese govern­ment to monitor dissi­dents and prevent citizens whose behavior they don’t like from purchasing goods and Bitcoin offers an alter­na­tive to centrally controlled digital money with a system that gives us back the person to person nature of cash, but in a digital Bitcoin is a digital asset that is issued and trans­ferred over a network of inter­con­nected computers that each indepen­dently verifies that everyone else is playing by the Where Did Bitcoin Originate? Bitcoin was invented by a person or group known by the pseudonym of Satoshi Nakamoto around No one knows Satoshi’s identity, and as far as we know, they’ve disap­peared and haven’t been heard from for On Feb , , Satoshi wrote about an early version of Bitcoin on an online forum for cypher­punks , people who work on cryptog­raphy technology and are concerned with individual privacy and Though this isn’t the first official release announce­ment of Bitcoin, it does contain a good summary of Satoshi’s motiva­tions. I’ve devel­oped a new open source P2P e‑cash system called It’s completely decen­tral­ized, with no central server or trusted parties, because every­thing is based on crypto proof instead of […] The root problem with conven­tional currency is all the trust that’s required to make it The central bank must be trusted not to debase the currency, but the history of fiat curren­cies is full of breaches of that Banks must be trusted to hold our money and transfer it electron­i­cally, but they lend it out in waves of credit bubbles with barely a fraction in We have to trust them with our privacy, trust them not to let identity thieves drain our Their massive overhead costs make micro­pay­ments impos­sible. A gener­a­tion ago, computer systems had a similar Before strong encryp­tion, users had to rely on password protec­tion to secure their files […] Then strong encryp­tion became avail­able to the masses, and trust was no longer Data could be secured in a way that was physi­cally impos­sible for others to access, no matter for what reason, no matter how good the excuse, no matter It’s time we had the same thing for With e‑currency based on crypto­graphic proof, without the need to trust a third party middleman, money can be secure and trans­ac­tions effort­less. […] Bitcoin’s solution is to use a network to check for In a nutshell, the network works like a distrib­uted timestamp server, stamping the first trans­ac­tion to spend a It takes advan­tage of the nature of infor­ma­tion being easy to spread but hard to For details on how it works, see the design paper at http: www.bitcoin.org bitcoin.pdf Satoshi Nakamoto What Problems Does Bitcoin Solve? Let’s break down some of Satoshi’s post to glean his motiva­tions. I’ve devel­oped a new open source P2P e‑cash system P2P stands for peer to peer and indicates a system where one person can interact with another without anyone in the middle, as equal You may recall P2P technolo­gies like Napster, Kazaa, and BitTor­rent, which first enabled people to share music and movies without an inter­me­diary. Satoshi designed Bitcoin to allow people to exchange e‑cash , electronic cash, without going through an inter­me­diary in much the same The software is open source , which means that anyone can see how it works and contribute to We don’t need to believe anything Satoshi wrote in his post about how the software We can look at the code and verify how it works for Further­more, we can evolve the function­ality of the system by changing the It’
